    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.89-91_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">8<del>9</del><add>8</add></fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        Public Library
                        Springfield, Missouri.
                        Tuesday 9:52 <hi rend="caps">A.M.</hi> 5/27 1958
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <salute>Dear Bard:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Last Saturday I spent the entire day enjoying again, "Song of the Indian Wars. I write a little <unclear/> verse myself &#8212; have sold 9,000 books. Your perfect meter and wonderful close rhymes make your poetry very pleasing. I have also read "The Crawl" and the one about the man named Glass &#8212; I forget his first name. They are <hi rend="underline">so</hi> vivid.</p>
                
                <p>The librarian here is one LeRoy Fox, a fig fellow, who was in your class at Emporia a few years ago. Springfield has a wonderful library, thanks to the efforts of Miss Vivian Maddox, who left in January.</p>
                
                <p>The years have not been kind to me. I have Parkinson's disease. I draw "total disability and Social Security. To pass the time, I solve puzzles,&#8212; crosswords and 
                
                    <note type="authorial">(over)</note>
                    
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.89-91_0002"/>
                    
                    Double Crostics. The latter I buy, 4 books at a time from Simon and Schuster. They are the most entrancing things I have ever run across. They appear, too, in Saturday Review and <hi rend="caps">N. Y.</hi> Times.</p>
                    
                <p>Thank you, Mr Neihardt for the pleasant hours your grand poems have afforded me.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Love</salute>
                
                    <signed>Perry Mason</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <note type="curatorial"><hi rend="caps">JOHN G. NEIHARDT CENTER</hi></note>
                
            </div1>
            
            
            <div1 type="enclosure">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26a.89-91_0003"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">9<del>1</del><add>0</add></fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Perry Mason</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>418 <hi rend="caps">E.</hi> Central</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Springfield, Mo.</addrLine>
                    </address>
                </opener>
                
                <lg>
                    <l>I've read John Neihardt all the livelong day</l>
                    <l>The poet, Neihardt has a pleasing way</l>
                    <l>Of weaving pretty words in perfect rhyme<add>,</add></l>
                    <l>More pleasantly I could pass the time.</l>
                    <l>In meter perfect are his stories told</l>
                    <l>Of fights twixt soldiers and red warriors bold.<add>Od</add></l>
                    <l>So grippingly you almost see the s<del>d</del><add>c</add>ene</l>
                    <l>The text is clear. No need to read between</l>
                    <l>The lines. I find I often play a game</l>
                    <l>I cover up a line and try to name</l>
                    <l>The word that Mr. Neihardt c<del>o</del><add>h</add>ose for rhyme,</l>
                    <l>And still I am surprised time after time</l>
                    <l>At words he brings into his perfect verse.</l>
                    <l>My poems, as I read seem worse and worse.</l>
                    <l>A friend, one who was priveleged to sit</l>
                    <l>In class told me <del>hh</del><add>Jo</add>hn Neihardt is a bit</l>
                    <l>Of man, but he is plenty big to me,</l>
                    <l>For he is what I ever want to be,</l>
                    <l>A poet full of eloquence and will,</l>
                    <l>One who can cleverly and ably fill</l>
                    <l>Up pages such as I've been readng here</l>
                    <l>While reading had I blink away a tear</l>
                    <l>From time to time by beauty rare begot.</l>
                    <l>Oh yes, John Neihardt is what I am not.</l>
                </lg>
                
            </div1>
            
            
